05395nam a22006495i 9780226522616DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018014120  a9780226522616  a(DE-B1597)550012  a(OCoLC)1053623582  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aNA111.5b.A45 2018 4aNA111.5b.A45 2018eb 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a725/.94223  aLH 60300qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/94187:1 aAllais, Lucia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesigns of Destruction :bThe Making of Monuments in the Twentieth Century /cLucia Allais. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b14 color plates, 123 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Monument Survival -- t1. “ Wardens of Civilization”. Conservation and Diplomacy at the 1931 Athens Conference -- t2. “ Battles Designed to Preserve”. The Allies’ Lists of Monuments in World War II -- t3. Unwitting City Planning. Maps of Monuments and the American Bombing of Europe, 1943–1945 -- t4. “ Stones Also Die”. UNESCO and the Decolonization of Museums, 1960–1975 -- t5. Integrities: The Salvage of Abu Simbel, 1960–1980 -- tCoda: Viscosities -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tArchives -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twentieth century was the most destructive in human history, but from its vast landscapes of ruins was born a new architectural type: the cultural monument. In the wake of World War I, an international movement arose which aimed to protect architectural monuments in large numbers, and regardless of style, hoping not only to keep them safe from future conflicts, but also to make them worthy of protection from more "idian forms of destruction. This movement was motivated by hopeful idealism as much as by a pragmatic belief in bureaucracy. An evolving group—including architects, intellectuals, art historians, archaeologists, curators, and lawyers—grew out of the new diplomacy of the League of Nations. During and after World War II, it became affiliated with the Allied Military Government, and was eventually absorbed by the UN as UNESCO. By the 1970s, this organization had begun granting World Heritage status to a global register of significant sites—from buildings to bridges, shrines to city centers, ruins to colossi. Examining key episodes in the history of this preservation effort—including projects for the Parthenon, for the Cathedral of St-Lô, the temples of Abu Simbel, and the Bamyian Buddahs —Lucia Allais demonstrates how the group deployed the notion of culture to shape architectural sites, and how architecture in turn shaped the very idea of global culture. More than the story of an emergent canon, Designs of Destruction emphasizes how the technical project of ensuring various buildings’ longevity jolted preservation into establishing a transnational set of codes, values, practices. Yet as entire nations’ monumental geographies became part of survival plans, Allais also shows, this paradoxically helped integrate technologies of destruction—from bombs to bulldozers—into cultural governance. Thus Designs of Destruction not only offers a fascinating narrative of cultural diplomacy, based on extensive archival findings; it also contributes an important new chapter in the intellectual history of modernity by showing the manifold ways architectural form is charged with concretizing abstract ideas and ideals, even in its destruction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArchitecturexConservation and restorationxInternational cooperationxHistoryy20th century. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxInternational coop